{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To solve it, we need to model the IDs in a Trie and determine the minimum bits to add so that no node representing a full ID is an ancestor of another node representing a full ID. This is equivalent to ensuring every leaf-path containing an ID is unique and no ID is a prefix of another.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_structure_analyzer",
      "instructions": "Analyze the problem to determine the optimal strategy for adding bits to a Trie. Specifically, identify how to handle nodes that represent the end of an ID. If an ID is a prefix of another ID, we must add bits to the shorter ID to push it deeper into the Trie or extend it so it is no longer a prefix. Determine if the problem can be modeled as finding the minimum number of nodes to add to a Trie such that no 'end-of-string' node is an ancestor of another 'end-of-string' node."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_algorithm_designer",
      "instructions": "Given a Trie where some nodes are marked as 'end-of-string', design a greedy approach or dynamic programming approach to calculate the minimum number of bits to append. Consider the constraints: N up to 10^5 and total length up to 10^6. The solution should likely involve a post-order traversal (bottom-up) of the Trie to decide at which nodes we must extend the strings to satisfy the condition that no ID is a prefix of another."
    },
    {
      "label": "complexity_and_implementation_verifier",
      "instructions": "Review the proposed Trie and greedy approach to ensure it meets the time complexity requirements (O(Total Length)) and memory constraints. Verify that the logic correctly handles the case where multiple IDs are identical or where one ID is a prefix of many others."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the Trie structural analysis with the greedy/DP strategy to produce a Python implementation. The final code must build a Trie from the input bitstrings, traverse it to identify prefix conflicts, and calculate the minimum bits needed to resolve these conflicts by extending the IDs."
}

